1
00:00:07,535 --> 00:00:11,308
Welcome back.

2
00:00:11,308 --> 00:00:18,315
Today we're going to have an introduction
to life cycle impact assessment.

3
00:00:18,315 --> 00:00:23,692
Our learning objectives for today
are going to be to connect the life cycle

4
00:00:23,692 --> 00:00:29,947
inventory to its impacts by defining this
life cycle impact assessment phase of LCA.

5
00:00:29,947 --> 00:00:32,887
And in doing so we're going to think about

6
00:00:32,887 --> 00:00:37,269
the complex challenges in
addressing some of these impacts.

7
00:00:37,269 --> 00:00:42,693
So in LCA, we work hard to get a detailed
list of the emissions and resources.

8
00:00:42,693 --> 00:00:44,773
And then we want to think about,

9
00:00:44,773 --> 00:00:49,748
how do we connect those to the impacts
on human and environmental health?

10
00:00:49,748 --> 00:00:55,223
So in terms of our sustainable development
goal categories, where we have for example

11
00:00:55,223 --> 00:01:00,483
responsible consumption and production or
sustainable cities and communities.

12
00:01:00,483 --> 00:01:05,331
We want to figure out how does that
impact these other sustainable

13
00:01:05,331 --> 00:01:10,549
development goal categories including
good health and well being.

14
00:01:10,549 --> 00:01:14,975
Clean water and sanitation,
climate action,

15
00:01:14,975 --> 00:01:18,193
life below water and life on land.

16
00:01:18,193 --> 00:01:23,091
This is the third and
last phase of a life cycle assessment.

17
00:01:23,091 --> 00:01:27,000
So we started with a goal and scope
definition, defining functional units

18
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:30,422
system boundaries,
figuring out the things we're comparing.

19
00:01:30,422 --> 00:01:33,819
Then we moved on to
the inventory of extractions and

20
00:01:33,819 --> 00:01:36,746
emissions associated with each scenario.

21
00:01:36,746 --> 00:01:38,110
What's the energy used?

22
00:01:38,110 --> 00:01:41,330
What's the pollution that's
coming into our air and water?

23
00:01:41,330 --> 00:01:45,817
And now we move to that last step,
what are the impacts of that inventory?

24
00:01:45,817 --> 00:01:49,516
And of course throughout a key
point is interpretation.

25
00:01:49,516 --> 00:01:54,314
The four categories of environmental
damage or impact that we focus on

26
00:01:54,314 --> 00:01:58,805
here are generally global impacts
that affect the entire world.

27
00:01:58,805 --> 00:02:02,724
Human health impacts which
affect humans in general.

28
00:02:02,724 --> 00:02:10,014
Ecosystem and biodiversity impact which
affect land, water, soil and species.

29
00:02:10,014 --> 00:02:14,891
And then resource use, which is thinking
about the water and land that's used and

30
00:02:14,891 --> 00:02:17,164
other resources, minerals as well.

31
00:02:17,164 --> 00:02:21,628
So one way to understand these is to
categorize some common environmental

32
00:02:21,628 --> 00:02:24,079
health impacts into these categories.

33
00:02:24,079 --> 00:02:26,189
So when we're talking about air pollution,

34
00:02:26,189 --> 00:02:29,198
we're usually talking about
human health impact categories.

35
00:02:29,198 --> 00:02:33,552
When we're thinking about climate change,
that's a global impact that can lead to

36
00:02:33,552 --> 00:02:36,881
increased temperatures and
extreme weather around the world.

37
00:02:36,881 --> 00:02:40,288
When we're looking at
species becoming extinct,

38
00:02:40,288 --> 00:02:43,463
that would fall in
the biodiversity category.

39
00:02:43,463 --> 00:02:47,590
When we talk about polluted water
that's related to resource use, but

40
00:02:47,590 --> 00:02:52,129
it also is connected to the human health
category of drinking water and food and

41
00:02:52,129 --> 00:02:54,013
of course to ecosystem health.

42
00:02:54,013 --> 00:02:59,233
And when we look at things like ocean
acidification and sea level rise that can

43
00:02:59,233 --> 00:03:04,873
result from climate change, those are also
impacts that happen around the world.

44
00:03:04,873 --> 00:03:09,574
And finally whenever we're focusing
on things like use of freshwater,

45
00:03:09,574 --> 00:03:13,361
that's a resource use category
that we're focusing on.

46
00:03:13,361 --> 00:03:17,983
One thing in life cycle impact assessment
is to think about the balance of

47
00:03:17,983 --> 00:03:23,289
the impacts that helps us think about the
balance between using the environment for

48
00:03:23,289 --> 00:03:26,660
what humans need versus
misusing the environment.

49
00:03:26,660 --> 00:03:31,325
And one example of this would be in
the US Dust Bowl in the 1930s and

50
00:03:31,325 --> 00:03:37,050
what happened there was after a period in
the twenties of relatively good rainfall.

51
00:03:37,050 --> 00:03:40,382
A lot of farmers in the Great Plains
decided to farm more

52
00:03:40,382 --> 00:03:43,135
intensively use deep
plowing techniques and

53
00:03:43,135 --> 00:03:47,348
new New developments in machinery
to farm relatively intensively.

54
00:03:47,348 --> 00:03:52,080
And so what that did is remove
the native grasses that normally

55
00:03:52,080 --> 00:03:56,454
trapped the soil during times
of drought and high winds.

56
00:03:56,454 --> 00:04:02,388
And so sure enough in 1930, when a drought
did come, the soil was no longer anchored.

57
00:04:02,388 --> 00:04:05,246
And that honor unanchored
soil turned into dust and

58
00:04:05,246 --> 00:04:08,901
then the high winds that came blew,
that dust high into the air and

59
00:04:08,901 --> 00:04:11,899
blackened the sky and
reached as far as New York City.

60
00:04:11,899 --> 00:04:15,556
This was happening throughout
the 1930s and unfortunately,

61
00:04:15,556 --> 00:04:19,537
it only intensified the economic impact
of the Great Depression that was

62
00:04:19,537 --> 00:04:21,571
already hitting the United States.

63
00:04:21,571 --> 00:04:26,251
And so it ended up leaving more
than 500,000 Americans homeless and

64
00:04:26,251 --> 00:04:29,381
many who died of dust pneumonia or
malnutrition.

65
00:04:29,381 --> 00:04:33,345
And so with things like life
cycle impact assessment,

66
00:04:33,345 --> 00:04:38,343
we want to think about the potential
impacts of what we're doing to our

67
00:04:38,343 --> 00:04:43,446
environment and how it might impact
people further on and all around.

68
00:04:43,446 --> 00:04:45,506
So, in considering impacts,

69
00:04:45,506 --> 00:04:49,559
we're facing new challenges
since the dust wall happened.

70
00:04:49,559 --> 00:04:54,482
New challenges in the magnitude of
these impacts because of technology and

71
00:04:54,482 --> 00:04:57,687
economic development,
we've accelerated and

72
00:04:57,687 --> 00:05:01,377
amplified the magnitude of
our footprint and impacts.

73
00:05:01,377 --> 00:05:04,067
And this is happening in multiple ways.

74
00:05:04,067 --> 00:05:08,886
It's happening in our spatial scale
where globalization distances impacts

75
00:05:08,886 --> 00:05:12,231
from the consumer,
from where those impacts occur.

76
00:05:12,231 --> 00:05:13,984
So when I consume something,

77
00:05:13,984 --> 00:05:17,569
I may not see any direct feedback
of the impact it's having.

78
00:05:17,569 --> 00:05:22,436
This also is challenging because with
globalization we require a global

79
00:05:22,436 --> 00:05:26,985
response and that makes governance
a challenge when trying to limit

80
00:05:26,985 --> 00:05:28,916
anything on a global scale.

81
00:05:28,916 --> 00:05:32,811
Another new challenge we're facing
is with the temporal scale.

82
00:05:32,811 --> 00:05:38,314
So our current actions may only have
visible impacts decades from now and

83
00:05:38,314 --> 00:05:43,276
so that makes it very hard to help
populations limit their actions

84
00:05:43,276 --> 00:05:48,160
based on future impacts that they
can't yet see or don't know.

85
00:05:48,160 --> 00:05:52,190
And this is all related to more
complex cause-effect chains.

86
00:05:52,190 --> 00:05:58,055
These are not always visible and so it's
crucial to use science and technology for

87
00:05:58,055 --> 00:06:02,985
diagnostics and to prevent irreversible
impacts that may happen far

88
00:06:02,985 --> 00:06:08,173
away in both time and space but
that can still critically impact others.

89
00:06:08,173 --> 00:06:13,149
Because as a reminder from before
we do not inherit the earth

90
00:06:13,149 --> 00:06:17,639
from our ancestors,
we borrow it from our children.

91
00:06:17,639 --> 00:06:23,039
So a summary of this video is the life
cycle impact assessment phase of LCA.

92
00:06:23,039 --> 00:06:27,802
Is how we connect that life cycle
inventory of the scenarios we're comparing

93
00:06:27,802 --> 00:06:31,553
to the ultimate impacts on
environmental and human health.

94
00:06:31,553 --> 00:06:34,104
That's the ultimate
question we want to answer.

95
00:06:34,104 --> 00:06:38,845
And because of global interconnectedness
and accelerating development of

96
00:06:38,845 --> 00:06:42,845
technology, it's increasingly
challenging to recognize and

97
00:06:42,845 --> 00:06:46,560
allocate the impacts of individual and
collective actions